  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Skipping Evacuation Coverage</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Sri Lanka's healthcare is limited for serious conditions. Medical evacuation to Singapore or Bangkok can cost $50,000+. This coverage is essential, not optional.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Expecting Reliable Internet Everywhere</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Internet varies significantly by location. Colombo and tourist areas have decent connectivity; rural areas can be very slow. If you need consistent video calls, plan your location carefully.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Ignoring Economic Realities</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Sri Lanka is recovering from a severe crisis. Power cuts, supply shortages, and economic volatility may occur. Have contingency plans and maintain perspective.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Bringing Cash</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">ATMs can be unreliable and have withdrawal limits. Bring sufficient USD or EUR cash as backup, and exchange at banks or authorized dealers for best rates.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating Travel Distances</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Sri Lanka is small but roads are slow. A 200km journey can take 5+ hours. Factor this into your planning, especially for airport connections.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Sri Lanka -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Sri Lanka</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Sri Lanka has free public healthcare but quality is basic. Private hospitals in Colombo are adequate for routine care. For anything serious, evacuation to Singapore, Bangkok, or India is standard.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Healthcare Facilities</h3>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 mb-6">
      <li><strong>Asiri Hospital</strong> - Colombo, largest private hospital chain</li>
      <li><strong>Nawaloka Hospital</strong> - Colombo, well-equipped private hospital</li>
      <li><strong>Lanka Hospitals</strong> - Colombo, modern private facility</li>
      <li><strong>Durdans Hospital</strong> - Colombo, established private hospital</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Medical Evacuation</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      For serious trauma, cardiac events, complex surgeries, or advanced cancer care, evacuation to Singapore (2 hours), Bangkok (4 hours), or Chennai, India (1.5 hours) is standard practice.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Sample Costs (Private, Without Insurance)</h3>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>GP visit:</strong> $15-30</li>
      <li><strong>Specialist:</strong> $30-60</li>
      <li><strong>Emergency room:</strong> $50-150</li>
      <li><strong>Hospital day:</strong> $100-300</li>
      <li><strong>Medical evacuation:</strong> $30,000-80,000</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Sri Lanka safe after the 2022 crisis?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes, for tourists and digital nomads. The political unrest has subsided, and daily life has normalized. Economic challenges remain (inflation, supply issues), but physical safety isn't a major concern. Tourist areas are functioning normally.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How is the internet in Sri Lanka?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Variable. Colombo has reasonable 4G and fiber connections. Tourist areas like Galle, Mirissa, and Ella have adequate coverage for most work. Rural areas can be slow or unreliable. For video-intensive work, choose your location carefully or work from Colombo coworking spaces.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I really need evacuation insurance?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Absolutely. Sri Lankan healthcare is not equipped for serious emergencies—heart attacks, major trauma, complex surgeries. Standard practice is evacuation to Singapore or Bangkok. Without insurance, this costs $50,000+. Don't gamble on this.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Where should I live in Sri Lanka?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Depends on priorities. Colombo for best internet and services. Galle/Unawatuna for beaches and colonial charm. Ella for hill country and nature. Arugam Bay for surfing. Kandy for culture and cooler climate. Most nomads move around to experience different areas.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is English widely spoken?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes, reasonably well. English is an official language from colonial times. Tourist areas, hotels, and educated Sri Lankans speak English. Basic communication is easy. For deeper interactions, Sinhala or Tamil helps but isn't essential.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I extend the Digital Nomad Visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. The visa can be extended for additional 6-month periods for $250 per extension. Apply before your current visa expires through the Department of Immigration.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Sri Lanka's Digital Nomad Visa offers access to an incredibly beautiful, culturally rich country at extremely affordable prices. The $2,000/month income requirement is accessible to many nomads, and your money goes remarkably far.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The tradeoffs are real: inconsistent internet outside major areas, limited healthcare requiring evacuation insurance, and ongoing economic recovery. Sri Lanka is best for adventurous nomads comfortable with developing-world conditions who prioritize experiences over convenience.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      If you want tropical living, cultural depth, and extreme affordability, and you're flexible about infrastructure, Sri Lanka delivers unique value. Just ensure you have proper insurance with evacuation coverage—this is non-negotiable.
    </p>

